Package com.gtnewhorizon.structurelib.structure

Class StructureUtility

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.gtnewhorizon.structurelib.structure.StructureUtility
  • public class StructureUtility
extends java.lang.Object
    A brief index of everything contained

    Control blocks

    A lot of these might seem to make more sense as a default function on IStructureElement. However, in that case javac generic will often fail to infer the type for you, so we have to define them as static methods

    If block

    Provide if block, allowing downstream call only if user specified conditions are meet (i.e. predicate returns true)
    • onlyIf(Predicate, IStructureElement) and its overloads

    Switch block

    Provide switch block, allowing to select a downstream element by using a key or index computed from trigger item and/or context object.
    • partitionBy(Function, IStructureElement[]) and its overloads

    Or Chain

    Provide a short-circuiting OR chain.
    • ofChain(IStructureElement[]) and its overloads

    Side effect

    Provide callbacks on various occasion
    • onElementPass(Consumer, IStructureElement): Call an callback upon element check success
    • onElementFail(Consumer, IStructureElement): Call an callback upon element check failure

    Other Primitives

    Error statement

    Unconditionally return false.
    • error()

    Context Object Change

    Switch the context object.
    • withContext(IStructureElement): switch context to the extended context

    Channel Change

    Change the channel. See Channels section on overview for more information.
    • withChannel(String, IStructureElement): switch channel using ChannelDataAccessor.withChannel(ItemStack, String) when a trigger item is present.

    Spawn hint particle

    Just spawn a hint. Do nothing otherwise. Useful when you want to override the hint provided by another structure element, or as a fallback to a structure element that is check only.
    • ofHint(int), ofHintDeferred(Supplier) and its overloads

    Actual Element

    These elements are elements that can actually do structure check, spawn hint and do auto place. Elements listed in above 2 sections are not going to be helpful without elements like these. They also serve as a reference implementation for your own custom IStructureElement implementations.

    Simple Block Element

    These accept one or more different block types in one location.
    • ofBlock(Block, int, Block, int), ofBlocksFlat(Map, Block, int), ofBlocksMap(Map, Block, int) and their overloads: the most basic form
    • ofBlockHint(Block, int, Block, int), ofBlocksFlatHint(Map, Block, int), ofBlocksMapHint(Map, Block, int): these are the same as above, but will not do autoplace
    • isAir(), notAir(): They are supplied by default under the identifier '-' and '+' respectively, but are provided here regardless in case you want to use them as a fallback.

    Complex Block Element

    In case your logic on determining which block is accepted is complex, use these.
    • ofBlockAdder(IBlockAdder, Block, int), ofBlockAdderHint(IBlockAdder, Block, int) and their overloads: hands off actual adder logic to an IBlockAdder you supplied. Save you the boilerplate of querying block type and block meta from World
    • ofBlocksTiered(ITierConverter, Object, BiConsumer, Function) and its overloads: accept a series of blocks that each may have different tier, but only allow one single tier for anywhere this element is used (e.g. coils).
    • ofTileAdder(ITileAdder, Block, int), ofSpecificTileAdder(BiPredicate, Class, Block, int): Similar to block adder, but for tile entities.

    Helper Methods

    These don't construct a IStructureElement, but is helpful to the instantiation or implementation of these.
    • survivalPlaceBlock(Block, int, World, int, int, int, IItemSource, EntityPlayer, Consumer) and its overloads: Helper method to cut common boilerplate for implementing IStructureElement.survivalPlaceBlock(Object, World, int, int, int, ItemStack, IItemSource, EntityPlayerMP, Consumer)
    • getPseudoJavaCode(World, ExtendedFacing, int, int, int, int, int, int, Function, int, int, int, boolean): Generate a structure code template from existing structure.
    • iterate(World, ExtendedFacing, int, int, int, int, int, int, boolean, int, int, int, IBlockPosConsumer, Runnable, Runnable) and its overloads: help iterate over a coordinate space.

      • ofBlocksTiered

        public static <T,​TIER> IStructureElementCheckOnly<T> ofBlocksTiered​(ITierConverter<TIER> tierExtractor,
                                                                          @Nullable
                                                                          TIER notSet,
                                                                          java.util.function.BiConsumer<T,​TIER> setter,
                                                                          java.util.function.Function<T,​TIER> getter)
        A more primitive variant of ofBlocksTiered(ITierConverter, List, Object, BiConsumer, Function) Main difference is this one is check only.

      • ofBlocksTiered

        public static <T,​TIER> IStructureElement<T> ofBlocksTiered​(ITierConverter<TIER> tierExtractor,
                                                                 @Nullable
                                                                 java.util.List<org.apache.commons.lang3.tuple.Pair<Block,​java.lang.Integer>> allKnownTiers,
                                                                 @Nullable
                                                                 TIER notSet,
                                                                 java.util.function.BiConsumer<T,​TIER> setter,
                                                                 java.util.function.Function<T,​TIER> getter)
        Element representing a component with different tiers. Your multi will accept any of them (as long as player does not mix tier (*)), but would like to know which is used. Player can use more blueprint to get hints denoting more advanced components.

        Above all else, you need to decide what type of tier you are going to use. For simpler cases, Integer is a good choice. You can also use an existing Enum. It can also be a String or a ResourceLocation, or basically anything. It doesn't even have to implement Comparable.

        If your tier extractor function returns null on any (Block, meta) pair, then it means this block is rejected. This also implies null can never be a valid tier.

        This structure element require you will reset the backing storage of getter in your own code, such that in every round of structure checking, the first call to getter would always return notSet. You can also make getter to return other value on that occasion to forcefully select a certain tier, but then you'd probably be better off using block adders or ofBlock(Block, int, Block, int) and its overloads

        There is yet no TileEntity counterpart of this utility. Feel free to submit a PR to add it.

        (*): Implementation wise, this structure element will only accept a block if its tier is the same as existing tier or if existing tier is unset (i.e. value of third argument). If there are multiple (block, tier) tuple for a given tier, then player will be allowed to use multiple kinds of blocks, but their tier is guaranteed to be the same.

        WARNING

        You SHOULD NOT return notSet from your tierExtractor. If you do so, we will have this chain of events:
        • at check start, tier is reset to notSet
        • the tier extractor returns notSet for first block, so since ofBlocksTiered finds your current tier is notSet, and the new block's tier is the same as that, so it's accepted
        • at 2nd, 3rd..., same thing in 2 happens
        • at last occurrence, player placed a valid block with a tier not notSet. ofBlocksTiered now sets your current tier to this tier, and accept the block
        • check got notified structure is sound, and tier is not notSet. it marks the structure as complete and start doing its business
        • Player enjoy a (probably) hilariously shaped multi and (probably) reduced build cost.

        Example Implementation

        Assume you have 16 tier, each map to one particular block's 16 different meta. You will usually want something like this 

         public class Tile extends TileEntity {
     private static final Block B = getTargetBlock();
     private static final IStructureDefinition<Tile> S = IStructureDefinition.<Tile>builder()
            // ... addShape, and other elements
            .addElement('c', ofBlocksTiered((b, m) -> b == B ? m : null,
                                            IntStream.range(0, 16).mapToObj(i -> Pair.of(B, i)).collect(Collectors.toList()),
                                            -1,
                                            (t, m) -> t.tier = m,
                                            t -> t.tier))
            .build();
     private int tier;

     public boolean check() {
         tier = -1;
         if (!S.check(...))
             return false;
         return isTierAcceptable(tier);
     }
 }
        Important bits of this example implementation:
        • The supplied ITierConverter returns null for an invalid block
        • Possible tier returned by ITierConverter is Integer object 0 to 15.
        • notSet is set to -1. tier got reset to this value by caller before calling into IStructureDefinition.check(Object, String, World, ExtendedFacing, int, int, int, int, int, int, boolean)
        • notSet is never a tier returned by ITierConverter.

        As a friendly reminder, the above characteristics are only for this simply demo, not as a general restriction imposed by ofBlocksTiered.

        Parameters:
        tierExtractor - a function to extract tier info from a block. This function can return null and will never be passed a null block or an invalid block meta. If this function returns null, then the block would be considered invalid.
        allKnownTiers - A list of all known tiers as of calling. Can be empty or null. No hint will be spawned if empty or null. Cannot have null elements. First element denotes the most primitive tier. Last element denotes the most advanced tier. If not all tiers are available at definition construction time, use lazy(Supplier) or its overloads to delay a bit. This list is only for hint particle spawning and survival build. The hint/autoplace code will choose 1st pair to spawn/place if trigger item has master channel data of 1, 2nd pair if 2, and so on.
        notSet - The value returned from getter when there were no tier info found in T yet. Cannot be null.
        getter - a function to retrieve the current tier from context object
        setter - a function to set the current tier into context object

      • ofChain

        @SafeVarargs
public static <T> IStructureElementChain<T> ofChain​(IStructureElement<T>... elementChain)
        This allows you to compose different IStructureElement to form a OR chain. As with any other OR operator, this one exhibits short-circuiting behavior, i.e. it will not call next structure element if previous one succeeded. (*)

        This allows you e.g. accept both a glass block using ofBlock(Block, int, Block, int) and a piece of air using isAir(). It will not attempt to capture any errors though, so next one will not be tried if previous one would crash.

        (*): For survival auto place, it will * REJECT, if all structure element REJECT * SKIP, if 1 or more structure element SKIP and the rest structure element (0 or more) REJECT * any other result, **immediately** upon any structure element returns these other results. This behavior is not 100% fixed and might change later on, but we will send the notice on a best effort basis.

        Take care while chaining, as it will try to call every structure element until it returns true. If none does it will finally return false.

      • defer

        public static <T> IStructureElementDeferred<T> defer​(java.util.function.BiFunction<T,​ItemStack,​IStructureElement<T>> to)
        This will defer the actual instantiation of structure element until the structure code is actually called. This will allow the structure element constructor to access properties only present on the context object (e.g. GT5 multiblock controller), e.g. hatch texture index to use. Use this if it might change for the same structure definition, e.g. if your structure might switch mode and change some parameter, while basically remain the same shape. Using this while lazy(Supplier) is enough will not break anything, but would incur unnecessary performance overhead.

        This variant also passes the trigger item to the function, allowing it to get more info.

        Parameters:
        to - downstream element supplier

        This will defer the actual instantiation of structure element until the first time structure code is actually called.

        Similar to defer, but caches the first returned element returned and won't call it again. Initialization is not thread safe. This will allow the structure element constructor to access properties only present on the context object (e.g. GT5 multiblock controller), e.g. hatch texture index to use.
